   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_6931_1818_08_08_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1818-08-08">8 August 1818</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Brinkley</persName>
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               When I consider that so many<lb/>
               days have elapsed since the return of<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">Harriet</persName> without my having<lb/>
               written a single line to you - I feel<lb/>
               quite ashamed of my seeming <choice>
                  <orig>ingrati=<lb/>
               =tude</orig>
                  <reg>ingratitude</reg>
               </choice> for the innumerable and essential<lb/>
               kindnesses that he received from everyone<lb/>
               at the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dunsink-Observatory_IE">Observatory</placeName> but chiefly from you<lb/>
               his second mother as he calls you. The<lb/>
               fact is that I felt so overwhelmed with<lb/>
               the account his sister and himself gave<lb/>
               me of the infinite trouble he occasioned to<lb/>
               your whole family and the infinite goodness<lb/>
               <del>wh</del> with which it was borne and with which<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_6931_1818_08_08_page02.jpg"/>
               not only the real wants but the caprices of an<lb/>
               invalid were attended to - that I could not find<lb/>
               words to express such thanks as would convey<lb/>
               my feelings and be acceptable to your generous<lb/>
               mind. We all thank you and the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">Doctor</persName> &amp;<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinM1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Mat <choice>
                     <orig>Brinkly</orig>
                     <reg>Brinkley</reg>
                  </choice>
               </persName> - and your gentle amiable<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinS1">daughter</persName> if not with our lips, with our hearts<lb/>
               every hour of the day - and also that good<lb/>
               excellent <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WellC1">Catherine</persName> for whom <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> has<lb/>
               made feel respect and admiration.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Since <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William's</persName> return he has been very<lb/>
               variable, during these days that we spent<lb/>
               at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PakeT2">Admiral Pakenhams</persName> he was <choice>
                  <orig>wonderful<lb/>
               -ly</orig>
                  <reg>wonderfully</reg>
               </choice> well. Since that he has had a <choice>
                  <orig>consider<lb/>
               -able</orig>
                  <reg>considerable</reg>
               </choice> return of pain - and consequent <choice>
                  <orig>feeble<lb/>
               -ness</orig>
                  <reg>feebleness</reg>
               </choice> and last night felt the crackling<lb/>
               noise in his head that he noticed while<lb/>
               at the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dunsink-Observatory_IE">observatory</placeName> - He is better today - no, I should<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_6931_1818_08_08_page03.jpg"/>
               say he is better just at this moment - for it<lb/>
               requires both morning and evening to <unclear>complete</unclear>
               <lb/>
               a day. Let me not thank you and the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">Doctor</persName>
               <lb/>
               for your kindness to him alone but for <add>your</add>
               <del>
                  <unclear>his</unclear>
               </del>
               <lb/>
               great goodness to my daughter - She<lb/>
               idolizes <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> B.</persName> and the seeds he has thrown<lb/>
               into her mind have not fallen into a barren<lb/>
               or ungrateful soil.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH4">Honora</persName> left us last week<lb/>
               for the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Meath_IE">County of Meath</placeName> on their way<lb/>
               to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Dubl</orig>
                     <reg>Dublin</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> and their grand expedition - <unclear>Which</unclear>
               <lb/>
               I trust will turn out as happily as it seems<lb/>
               well planned. I fear their passage through<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> will be so short that they cannot<lb/>
               make their way to you - but they will be<lb/>
               to be heard of at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Merrion-Street-31_IE">31 Merrion Street</placeName>.<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               Adieu my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinE1">
                  <hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Brinkley</persName> with most<lb/>
               affectionate remembrances to the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
               </persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinS1">Miss B.</persName>
               <lb/>
               Believe me very sincerely your Obliged<lb/>
               and attached<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">F. Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <closer>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_6931_1818_08_08_page04.jpg"/>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Brinkley</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>at the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dunsink-Observatory_IE">Observatory</placeName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
